I"é<p>Cartesian anxiety refers to the incessant human craving for an absolute ground, an absolute reference point with respect to which they can predictably operate. This search for an objective â€œoutsideâ€ world <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/world-models-reflect-ideological-structures">is reflected in the ideal of mind</a> as a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/minds-are-like-mirrors-of-nature">mirror of nature</a>. Through cognitive dissonance, Cartesian anxiety discourages one from considering any <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/experientialism-breaks-the-subjectivism-objectivism-dichotomy">belief structure which is at odds with objectivism</a> and the sense of the world as an absolute ground.</p>
